{"allContent":{"docusaurus-plugin-content-docs":{"default":{"loadedVersions":[{"versionName":"current","label":"Next","banner":null,"badge":false,"noIndex":false,"className":"docs-version-current","path":"/whitepaper","tagsPath":"/whitepaper/tags","isLast":true,"routePriority":-1,"sidebarFilePath":"D:\\work\\Documentation\\sidebars\\whitepaper.ts","contentPath":"D:\\work\\Documentation\\docs","docs":[{"id":"00-abstract","title":"Abstract","description":"Following the wake of centralized exchanges, early decentralized exchanges led the DeFi movement using order books and liquidity pools. Yet DeFi users still lacked a fully decentralized way to onramp from fiat to crypto and offramp back to fiat.","source":"@site/docs/00-abstract.md","sourceDirName":".","slug":"/abstract","permalink":"/whitepaper/abstract","draft":false,"unlisted":false,"tags":[],"version":"current","sidebarPosition":0,"frontMatter":{"id":"00-abstract","sidebar_position":0,"title":"Abstract","slug":"abstract"},"sidebar":"whitepaperSidebar","next":{"title":"1. The Vision","permalink":"/whitepaper/the-vision"}},{"id":"01-1-the-vision","title":"1. The Vision","description":"1.1 From \"ramps\" to a privacy and credibility based economy","source":"@site/docs/01-1-the-vision.md","sourceDirName":".","slug":"/the-vision","permalink":"/whitepaper/the-vision","draft":false,"unlisted":false,"tags":[],"version":"current","sidebarPosition":1,"frontMatter":{"id":"01-1-the-vision","sidebar_position":1,"title":"1. The Vision","slug":"the-vision"},"sidebar":"whitepaperSidebar","previous":{"title":"Abstract","permalink":"/whitepaper/abstract"},"next":{"title":"2. Design Goals and Non-Goals","permalink":"/whitepaper/design-goals-and-non-goals"}},{"id":"02-2-design-goals-and-non-goals","title":"2. Design Goals and Non-Goals","description":"2.1 Goals","source":"@site/docs/02-2-design-goals-and-non-goals.md","sourceDirName":".","slug":"/design-goals-and-non-goals","permalink":"/whitepaper/design-goals-and-non-goals","draft":false,"unlisted":false,"tags":[],"version":"current","sidebarPosition":2,"frontMatter":{"id":"02-2-design-goals-and-non-goals","sidebar_position":2,"title":"2. Design Goals and Non-Goals","slug":"design-goals-and-non-goals"},"sidebar":"whitepaperSidebar","previous":{"title":"1. The Vision","permalink":"/whitepaper/the-vision"},"next":{"title":"3. System Overview","permalink":"/whitepaper/system-overview"}},{"id":"02-how-the-protocol-works-today-high-level-not-vendor-locked","title":"How the protocol works today (high level, not vendor-locked)","description":"1. Placing orders. A user clicks \"Buy USDC\" (or \"Sell USDC\") and enters an amount. Users can import an existing wallet address to start transacting.","source":"@site/docs/02-how-the-protocol-works-today-high-level-not-vendor-locked.md","sourceDirName":".","slug":"/how-the-protocol-works-today-high-level-not-vendor-locked","permalink":"/whitepaper/how-the-protocol-works-today-high-level-not-vendor-locked","draft":false,"unlisted":false,"tags":[],"version":"current","sidebarPosition":2,"frontMatter":{"id":"02-how-the-protocol-works-today-high-level-not-vendor-locked","sidebar_position":2,"title":"How the protocol works today (high level, not vendor-locked)","slug":"how-the-protocol-works-today-high-level-not-vendor-locked"}},{"id":"03-3-system-overview","title":"3. System Overview","description":"3.1 Actors","source":"@site/docs/03-3-system-overview.md","sourceDirName":".","slug":"/system-overview","permalink":"/whitepaper/system-overview","draft":false,"unlisted":false,"tags":[],"version":"current","sidebarPosition":3,"frontMatter":{"id":"03-3-system-overview","sidebar_position":3,"title":"3. System Overview","slug":"system-overview"},"sidebar":"whitepaperSidebar","previous":{"title":"2. Design Goals and Non-Goals","permalink":"/whitepaper/design-goals-and-non-goals"},"next":{"title":"4. Cryptographic Primitives & Proof Integration","permalink":"/whitepaper/cryptographic-primitives-proof-integration"}},{"id":"03-why-credibility-matters-and-why-over-collateralization-shouldnt-be-the-only-answer","title":"Why credibility matters (and why over-collateralization shouldn't be the only answer)","description":"Traditional DeFi often reaches for heavy collateral to feel safe. That works for some instruments, but it makes everyday finance clunky and exclusionary. Credibility-based DeFi says: let peers earn limits, speed, and price by behaving well over time, and let ZK proofs protect privacy while doing so.","source":"@site/docs/03-why-credibility-matters-and-why-over-collateralization-shouldnt-be-the-only-answer.md","sourceDirName":".","slug":"/why-credibility-matters-and-why-over-collateralization-shouldnt-be-the-only-answer","permalink":"/whitepaper/why-credibility-matters-and-why-over-collateralization-shouldnt-be-the-only-answer","draft":false,"unlisted":false,"tags":[],"version":"current","sidebarPosition":3,"frontMatter":{"id":"03-why-credibility-matters-and-why-over-collateralization-shouldnt-be-the-only-answer","sidebar_position":3,"title":"Why credibility matters (and why over-collateralization shouldn't be the only answer)","slug":"why-credibility-matters-and-why-over-collateralization-shouldnt-be-the-only-answer"}},{"id":"04-4-cryptographic-primitives-proof-integration","title":"4. Cryptographic Primitives & Proof Integration","description":"4.1 Proofs for Identity and Payments","source":"@site/docs/04-4-cryptographic-primitives-proof-integration.md","sourceDirName":".","slug":"/cryptographic-primitives-proof-integration","permalink":"/whitepaper/cryptographic-primitives-proof-integration","draft":false,"unlisted":false,"tags":[],"version":"current","sidebarPosition":4,"frontMatter":{"id":"04-4-cryptographic-primitives-proof-integration","sidebar_position":4,"title":"4. Cryptographic Primitives & Proof Integration","slug":"cryptographic-primitives-proof-integration"},"sidebar":"whitepaperSidebar","previous":{"title":"3. System Overview","permalink":"/whitepaper/system-overview"},"next":{"title":"5. Trade Protocol (On- and Off-Ramp)","permalink":"/whitepaper/trade-protocol-on-and-off-ramp"}},{"id":"05-5-trade-protocol-on-and-off-ramp","title":"5. Trade Protocol (On- and Off-Ramp)","description":"We formalize the order lifecycle as a state machine with timeouts:","source":"@site/docs/05-5-trade-protocol-on-and-off-ramp.md","sourceDirName":".","slug":"/trade-protocol-on-and-off-ramp","permalink":"/whitepaper/trade-protocol-on-and-off-ramp","draft":false,"unlisted":false,"tags":[],"version":"current","sidebarPosition":5,"frontMatter":{"id":"05-5-trade-protocol-on-and-off-ramp","sidebar_position":5,"title":"5. Trade Protocol (On- and Off-Ramp)","slug":"trade-protocol-on-and-off-ramp"},"sidebar":"whitepaperSidebar","previous":{"title":"4. Cryptographic Primitives & Proof Integration","permalink":"/whitepaper/cryptographic-primitives-proof-integration"},"next":{"title":"6. Proof-of-Credibility (Reputation & Matching)","permalink":"/whitepaper/proof-of-credibility-reputation-matching"}},{"id":"06-6-proof-of-credibility-reputation-matching","title":"6. Proof-of-Credibility (Reputation & Matching)","description":"P2P Protocol works using a unique on-chain reputation system which not only builds up user trust and privileges but actively helps prevent fraudulent activity within the P2P landscape.","source":"@site/docs/06-6-proof-of-credibility-reputation-matching.md","sourceDirName":".","slug":"/proof-of-credibility-reputation-matching","permalink":"/whitepaper/proof-of-credibility-reputation-matching","draft":false,"unlisted":false,"tags":[],"version":"current","sidebarPosition":6,"frontMatter":{"id":"06-6-proof-of-credibility-reputation-matching","sidebar_position":6,"title":"6. Proof-of-Credibility (Reputation & Matching)","slug":"proof-of-credibility-reputation-matching"},"sidebar":"whitepaperSidebar","previous":{"title":"5. Trade Protocol (On- and Off-Ramp)","permalink":"/whitepaper/trade-protocol-on-and-off-ramp"},"next":{"title":"7. Fraud Prevention","permalink":"/whitepaper/fraud-prevention"}},{"id":"07-7-fraud-prevention","title":"7. Fraud Prevention","description":"7.1 How Reputation Prevents Fraud","source":"@site/docs/07-7-fraud-prevention.md","sourceDirName":".","slug":"/fraud-prevention","permalink":"/whitepaper/fraud-prevention","draft":false,"unlisted":false,"tags":[],"version":"current","sidebarPosition":7,"frontMatter":{"id":"07-7-fraud-prevention","sidebar_position":7,"title":"7. Fraud Prevention","slug":"fraud-prevention"},"sidebar":"whitepaperSidebar","previous":{"title":"6. Proof-of-Credibility (Reputation & Matching)","permalink":"/whitepaper/proof-of-credibility-reputation-matching"},"next":{"title":"8. Dispute Resolution","permalink":"/whitepaper/dispute-resolution"}},{"id":"08-8-dispute-resolution","title":"8. Dispute Resolution","description":"Every instance of data sharing within the Protocol takes place via ZK principled evidence. If a user files a dispute within the DApp over the Protocol, the other party can issue and share a proof of their transaction without submitting additional personal data. A smart contract settles the dispute automatically when verifiers attest that the required statement has been proven; otherwise bonds and fees route per policy.","source":"@site/docs/08-8-dispute-resolution.md","sourceDirName":".","slug":"/dispute-resolution","permalink":"/whitepaper/dispute-resolution","draft":false,"unlisted":false,"tags":[],"version":"current","sidebarPosition":8,"frontMatter":{"id":"08-8-dispute-resolution","sidebar_position":8,"title":"8. Dispute Resolution","slug":"dispute-resolution"},"sidebar":"whitepaperSidebar","previous":{"title":"7. Fraud Prevention","permalink":"/whitepaper/fraud-prevention"},"next":{"title":"9. Pricing & Oracle Mechanics","permalink":"/whitepaper/pricing-oracle-mechanics"}},{"id":"09-9-pricing-oracle-mechanics","title":"9. Pricing & Oracle Mechanics","description":"The Protocol determines indicative pricing using built-in oracle adapters that aggregate rates from selected exchanges and P2P venues into a median/TWAP with fallbacks. These oracles analyze price data from a variety of both centralized and P2P exchanges to determine the trading price for the stablecoin-fiat pair in question.","source":"@site/docs/09-9-pricing-oracle-mechanics.md","sourceDirName":".","slug":"/pricing-oracle-mechanics","permalink":"/whitepaper/pricing-oracle-mechanics","draft":false,"unlisted":false,"tags":[],"version":"current","sidebarPosition":9,"frontMatter":{"id":"09-9-pricing-oracle-mechanics","sidebar_position":9,"title":"9. Pricing & Oracle Mechanics","slug":"pricing-oracle-mechanics"},"sidebar":"whitepaperSidebar","previous":{"title":"8. Dispute Resolution","permalink":"/whitepaper/dispute-resolution"},"next":{"title":"10. Liquidity & Market Design","permalink":"/whitepaper/liquidity-market-design"}},{"id":"10-10-liquidity-market-design","title":"10. Liquidity & Market Design","description":"10.1 Current Liquidity Model","source":"@site/docs/10-10-liquidity-market-design.md","sourceDirName":".","slug":"/liquidity-market-design","permalink":"/whitepaper/liquidity-market-design","draft":false,"unlisted":false,"tags":[],"version":"current","sidebarPosition":10,"frontMatter":{"id":"10-10-liquidity-market-design","sidebar_position":10,"title":"10. Liquidity & Market Design","slug":"liquidity-market-design"},"sidebar":"whitepaperSidebar","previous":{"title":"9. Pricing & Oracle Mechanics","permalink":"/whitepaper/pricing-oracle-mechanics"},"next":{"title":"11. Security Model","permalink":"/whitepaper/security-model"}},{"id":"11-11-security-model","title":"11. Security Model","description":"TECH TODO","source":"@site/docs/11-11-security-model.md","sourceDirName":".","slug":"/security-model","permalink":"/whitepaper/security-model","draft":false,"unlisted":false,"tags":[],"version":"current","sidebarPosition":11,"frontMatter":{"id":"11-11-security-model","sidebar_position":11,"title":"11. Security Model","slug":